// [jpw]  The scancode mappings for the ThinkPad X40.
//	  This file should be named "thinkpadx40"


// Provide aliases for the raw scancodes (keycode in X-parlance).
// The corresponding scancode-to-Xkeysym translation occurs in the
// "symbols/thinkpadx40" file.

// The following files will provide you with the following information:
// 
// /usr/include/X11/keysymdef.h:
//      The standard X keysyms (not keycodes).
// /usr/include/X11/XF86keysym.h:
//      The X keysyms (not keycodes) defined by XFree86 and now
//      considered standard.
// /usr/share/X11/XKeysymDB:
//      Contains a few additional X keysyms (not keycodes) not present
//      in the two *.h files mentioned above.
// /usr/share/X11/xkb/keycodes/xfree86:
// /usr/share/X11/xkb/keycodes/evdev:
//      These two files contain the standard aliases for the raw
//      keyboard scancodes.
//      Note that the first file is invalid if you're using the
//      "evdev" keyboard module instead of "keyboard".
//
// When looking up keysyms in the aforementioned files, strip off the
// leading "XK_" to get the actual keysym name.
//
// The keycode aliases require no translation.


//=============================================================================
//  Keycodes
//=============================================================================


// The keycodes generated by the special ThinkPad keys.  Note that the
// xkb_symbols for these keys do not use the aliases defined below, to
// better provide portability and customization.
//
// The main purpose of this custom "xkb_keycodes" section is to
// eliminate the Scroll Lock indicator, since the ThinkPad X40 (and
// other models, I suspect) have no Scroll Lock indicator.

default partial
xkb_keycodes "X_series" {
    // There will be warnings from xkbcomp because of multiple definitions.
    virtual indicator 3 = "None";

    // keycode: 151
    alias <FN> = 151;
    // keycode: 166
    alias <SBAK> = 166;
    // keycode: 167
    alias <SFWD> = 167;
};
